  "description": "¶Entry conditions Use set-based structures only when you can:\nIdentify a finite or well-defined collection of elements. Decide membership clearly (no ambiguous membership rules). Represent relations as explicit pairs of elements. If membership is undefined or dynamic without rules, do not treat it as a set.\n¶Definitions A set SS is a collection of elements with clear membership. ¶Vocabulary (plain language) Set: a named collection of distinct items. Element: one item that may belong to a set. Ordered pair: a two-item list where order matters, written (x,y)(x,y). Membership: the rule that decides whether an element is in the set. ¶Symbols used S,TS, T: sets. x∈Sx \\in S: \u0026ldquo;xx is an element of SS.\u0026rdquo; ¶Intuition Think of a set as a named bucket of distinct items. What matters is whether an item is in the bucket or not.\n",
